{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"178fb46f-df50-4f23-ad28-f9bcdc188c8c","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the container:**\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Find your app's PID:**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**3. Collect the trace** (30 seconds is usually enough):\n```bash\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n**4. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:<path>/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**5. Analyze** by opening the `.nettrace` in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert to speedscope format:\n```bash\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\nThen open at [speedscope.app](https://speedscope.app).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools (distroless image), use **`DOTNET_EnableDiagnostics=1`** and a sidecar with `dotnet-monitor` instead.\n- For production, consider [`dotnet-monitor`](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/dotnet-monitor) as a sidecar — it exposes an HTTP API to collect traces without exec'ing in.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"511800ab-ff2f-402a-9f04-e69a4fddd7a8","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise, practical advice.","outputTokens":431,"requestId":"A0C4:234D18:C300A5:F0C835:6A013133"},"id":"408d44d9-570b-41ad-8ede-973ff9714134","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:30:36.520Z","parentId":"cd3f8230-254c-492b-ac04-de16378baef9"}
